{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Textarea · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Textarea</h1>
    <p class="lead">A multi-line text field that grows with its content.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>Basic</h2>
    <p>Add <code>.textarea</code> to any <code>&lt;textarea&gt;</code>. The fixed-height contract from <a class="link" href="/input">.input</a> drops, so <code>rows</code> and content drive the height. The resize handle is vertical only, so the width tracks the parent.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="field" style="max-width: 24rem;">
      <label for="basicTextarea" class="field__label">Notes</label>
      <textarea class="textarea" id="basicTextarea" rows="3" placeholder="Anything else we should know?"></textarea>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Sizes</h2>
    <p>Three sizes match the input scale so a textarea sits beside an input in the same row. Add <code>.textarea--compact</code> or <code>.textarea--roomy</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="demo-stack" style="max-width: 24rem;">
      <textarea class="textarea textarea--compact" rows="2" placeholder="Small"></textarea>
      <textarea class="textarea" rows="2" placeholder="Default"></textarea>
      <textarea class="textarea textarea--roomy" rows="2" placeholder="Large"></textarea>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Helper text</h2>
    <p>Use <code>.field__description</code> below the field for short hints. Wire it to the textarea with <code>aria-describedby</code> so screen readers announce it.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="field" style="max-width: 24rem;">
      <label for="bioTextarea" class="field__label">Bio</label>
      <textarea class="textarea" id="bioTextarea" rows="3" aria-describedby="bioHelp"></textarea>
      <div id="bioHelp" class="field__description">A sentence or two. Visible on your public profile.</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Browser validation</h2>
    <p>Pair native constraint attributes (<code>required</code>, <code>minlength</code>, <code>maxlength</code>) with the <code>:user-invalid</code> pseudo. The browser fires it after the user interacts with the field, and clears it the moment the value satisfies the constraints.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <form class="demo-stack" style="max-width: 24rem;" onsubmit="event.preventDefault()">
      <div class="field">
        <label for="reqMessage" class="field__label">Message</label>
        <textarea class="textarea" id="reqMessage" rows="3" required minlength="10" placeholder="At least 10 characters"></textarea>
        <div class="field__description">Hit Submit with fewer than 10 characters to trigger <code>:user-invalid</code>. Type past 10 and the red clears on its own.</div>
      </div>
      <button type="submit" class="btn btn--primary">Submit</button>
    </form>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Server validation</h2>
    <p>Set <code>aria-invalid="true"</code> from your form library. The attribute is sticky, and Stisla just paints while it's present. Pair with a <code>.field__error</code> message tied via <code>aria-describedby</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="demo-stack" style="max-width: 24rem;">
      <div class="field">
        <label for="srvFeedback" class="field__label">Feedback</label>
        <textarea
          class="textarea"
          id="srvFeedback"
          rows="3"
          aria-invalid="true"
          aria-describedby="srvFeedbackError">Way too short.</textarea>
        <div id="srvFeedbackError" class="field__error">Please write at least 50 characters.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Disabled &amp; readonly</h2>
    <p><code>disabled</code> blocks interaction and dims the field. <code>readonly</code> keeps the value selectable for copy but rejects edits. The bg shifts a tier so you can see at a glance that the field is selectable but not editable.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="demo-stack" style="max-width: 24rem;">
      <textarea class="textarea" rows="2" disabled>Disabled</textarea>
      <textarea class="textarea" rows="2" readonly>Readonly</textarea>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>These variables retune <code>.textarea</code> independently of <code>.input</code>. Override on the field itself, on a parent scope, or on <code>:root</code>. <code>--textarea-height</code> acts as a min-height floor (the field grows past it as content fills in).</p>
    <p>On touch devices (<code>@media (pointer: coarse)</code>) <code>--textarea-font-size</code> is bumped to <code>1rem</code> so iOS Safari doesn't zoom the viewport on focus. The browser auto-zooms any field with computed font-size below 16px and never zooms back; desktop keeps the tighter default.</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Variable</th>
          <th>Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-radius</code></td>
          <td>Corner radius; the compact and roomy variants reassign this</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-height</code></td>
          <td>Min-height floor; the field grows past this with content. The compact and roomy variants reassign this</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-padding-inline</code></td>
          <td>Horizontal padding; the compact and roomy variants reassign this</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-font-size</code></td>
          <td>Text size; the compact and roomy variants reassign this</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-bg</code></td>
          <td>Background; <code>readonly</code> shifts a tier</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-color</code></td>
          <td>Text color</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-border-width</code></td>
          <td>Border thickness</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-border-color</code></td>
          <td>Border color; validation hooks flip this to <code>--st-danger</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--textarea-placeholder</code></td>
          <td>Placeholder text color</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
